definition.value: An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of thymidine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of 3'-deoxythymidine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of 2'-deoxyuridine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic diphosphate formed by condensation between the beta-phospho group of thymidine diphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of uridine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of xanthosine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of inosine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of guanosine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of cytidine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
An organic triphosphate formed by condensation between the gamma-phospho group of adenosine 5'-triphosphate and ethanol.
The monocarboxylic acid anion formed by removal of a proton from the carboxy group of soyasaponin III. It is the major microspecies present at pH 7.3.
1,3-Thiazole substituted at C-2, -4 and -5 with carboxy, methyl and 2-(phosphonooxy)ethyl groups respectively.
An EC 2.4.2.* (pentosyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of a NAD(+) ADP-ribosyltransferase (EC 2.4.2.30).
An  EC 2.4.99.* (glycosyltransferases transferring other glycosyl groups) inhibitor that interferes with the action of a sialyltransferase.
The monocarboxylic acid anion formed from soyasaponin I. It is the major microspecies present at pH 7.3.
A glycosylmannose derivative in which 2-O-acetyl-alpha-D-abequopyranose is linked alpha(1->3) to alpha-D-mannopyranose.
A myo-inositol trisphosphate having the three phosphate groups at the 3-, 4-, and 6-positions.
A myo-inositol pentakisphosphate that consists of myo-inositol having the five phospho groups located at positions 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6 as well as a diphospho group at position 1.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of icosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group. Major species at pH 7.3.

The tricarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of (S,S,S)-nicotianamine, resulting from deprotonation of the central carboxy group and zwitterion formation of the other two. One of two major microspecies at physiological pH.
A myo-inositol pentakisphosphate that consists of myo-inositol having the five phospho groups located at positions 1, 2, 4, 5 and 6 as well as a diphospho group at position 3.
A 1D-myo-inositol bis(diphosphate) tetrakisphosphate having the two diphospho groups located at positions 1 and 5.
A 1D-myo-inositol bis(diphosphate) tetrakisphosphate having the two diphospho groups located at positions 3 and 5.
A 1D-myo-inositol bis(diphosphate) tetrakisphosphate having the two diphospho groups located at positions 1 and 3.
A myo-inositol tetrakisphosphate that consists of myo-inositol having the four phospho groups located at positions 3, 4, 5 and 6 as well as a diphospho group at position 1.
A myo-inositol tetrakisphosphate that consists of myo-inositol having the four phospho groups located at positions 1, 4, 5 and 6 as well as a diphospho group at position 3.
A myo-inositol tetrakisphosphate that consists of myo-inositol having the four phospho groups located at positions 2, 3, 4 and 6 as well as a diphospho group at position 5.
A myo-inositol bis(diphosphate) trisphosphate having the three phospho groups located at positions 4, 5 and 6 and the two diphospho groups at positions 1 and 3.
A 1D-myo-inositol bis(diphosphate) trisphosphate having the three phospho groups located at positions 1, 4 and 6 and the two diphospho groups at positions 3 and 5.
A 1D-myo-inositol bis(diphosphate) trisphosphate having the three phospho groups located at positions 3, 4 and 6 and the two diphospho groups at positions 1 and 5.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of mycophenolic acid.
A carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of an oxylipin (any member of the group of bioactive lipids made by oxidation of polyunsaturated fatty acids).
An L-alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base formed when discadenine (a 6-isopentenylaminopurine having a 3-amino-3-carboxypropyl group attached at the 3-position) is deprotonated.
The 7-oxime of dehydroepiandrosterone, substituted on the oxime oxygen by a carboxymethyl group.
The alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of homomethionine obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of an icosanoid, formed when the carboxy group is deprotonated.
Any straight-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of a mono-hydroxy epoxy icosatrienoic acid formed when the carboxy group of the carboxylic acid is deprotonated.
A glycotriaosylceramide having beta-D-galactosyl-(1->6)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucose as the glycotriaosyl component.
A carboxylic ester-lactam that is a synthetic DDM (didehydroxymycobactin)-like lipopeptide.
A ceramide compound formed by the replacement of the glycosidic hydroxy group of a cyclic form of a monosaccharide (or derivative) by a ceramide group.
A eicosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of a leukotriene.
An icosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of a prostanoid.
A carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of a sialic acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A prostanoid anion that is the conjugate base of a thromboxane.

An inorganic sulfate salt obtained by reaction of sulfuric acid with two equivalents of ammonia. A high-melting (decomposes above 280degreeC) white solid which is very soluble in water (70.6 g/100 g water at 0degreeC; 103.8 g/100 g water at 100degreeC), it is widely used as a fertilizer for alkaline soils.

An ammonium salt obtained by reaction of ammonia with acetic acid. A deliquescent white crystalline solid, it has a relatively low melting point (114degreeC) for a salt. Used as a food acidity regulator, although no longer approved for this purpose in the EU.
A trisaccharide consisting of L-fucose linked alpha(1->2') to a beta-lactose unit.
A alpha-L-Fucp-(1->2)-beta-D-Galp-(1->3)-D-Galp that has beta-configuration at the anomeric hydroxy group.
